SIMPLE: stigma
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stigma
<hw>Stig"ma</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> E.
<plw>Stigmas</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>, L. <plw>Stigmata</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., a mark, a brand, from Gr. <?/, <?/, the
prick or mark of a pointed instrument, a spot, mark, from <?/ to prick,
to brand. See <er>Stick</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
mark made with a burning iron; a brand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any mark of infamy or disgrace; sign of moral
blemish; stain or reproach caused by dishonorable conduct; reproachful
characterization.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The blackest <qex>stigma</qex> that can be fastened upon him.</q>
<rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All such slaughters were from thence called Bartelmies, simply in
a perpetual <qex>stigma</qex> of that butchery.</q> <rj><qau>Sir G.
Buck.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>That part of a pistil which has no
epidermis, and is fitted to receive the pollen. It is usually the
terminal portion, and is commonly somewhat glutinous or viscid. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Stamen</er> and of <er>Flower</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>A small spot, mark, scar, or a
minute hole; -- applied especially to a spot on the outer surface of a
Graafian follicle, and to spots of intercellular substance in scaly
epithelium, or to minute holes in such spots.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Pathol.)</fld> <def>A red speck upon the skin,
produced either by the extravasation of blood, as in the bloody sweat
characteristic of certain varieties of religious ecstasy, or by
capillary congestion, as in the case of drunkards.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One of the external
openings of the tracheae of insects, myriapods, and other arthropods; a
spiracle.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One of the apertures of the pulmonary
sacs of arachnids. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Scorpion</er>.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>One of the apertures of the gill of an ascidian, and
of Amphioxus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A point so connected by any law
whatever with another point, called an <xex>index</xex>, that as the
index moves in any manner in a plane the first point or stigma moves in
a determinate way in the same plane.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>Marks
believed to have been supernaturally impressed upon the bodies of
certain persons in imitation of the wounds on the crucified body of
Christ. See def. 5, above.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stigmaria</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
